AGI - Today Japan commemorates the 30th anniversary of the attack with sarin gases at the Tokyo Metro, which killed 13 people and killed more than 5,800. It is on March 20, 1995, when five members of the Aum Shinrikyo> sect drop bags of a nerve gas, developed by the Nazis, inside the train of the commuters in the morning, piercing the sacks with sharp umbrella tips before fleeing.
<h2> The attack
Trains continue, trapping passengers inside with deadly fumes.> Once stopped, passengers leave the stations vomiting and fighting to breathe, with rescuers providing assistance to the sides of the road. The attack kills, as said, 13 people, while a fourteenth will die in 2020 after severe brain damage in the attack. Over 5,800 other people remain wounded, and many of them still suffer from vision problems, fatigue and psychological trauma.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The cult leader
The cult leader, Shoko Asahara>, almost blind, was executed in 2018 along with 12 disciples for attack and other violent crimes. Asahara, whose real name was Chizuo Matsumoto>, preached the imminent arrival of the apocalypse, ensuring that the massacre could elevate the souls of the followers to a higher kingdom. Aum was dissolved, but its deceased leader is still venerated in Japan by about 1,600 members of the heir groups: According to experts, such groups contact young recruits in secret, both in person and through social media and messaging apps, spreading posts in which they claim that Aum's crimes were misrepresented.
